First, we recognize that this equation is a convolution involving the divisor function \( d(n) \) and the function \( f \). Using the Möbius inversion formula, we determine that \( f \) must be the Möbius function convoluted with the constant function 1. We then derive that \( f \) is a multiplicative function. For a prime power \( p^k \), we find that \( f(p^k) = 1 - p \) for any \( k \geq 1 \). For a composite number \( n \) with prime factorization \( n = \prod_{i=1}^r p_i^{k_i} \), the function \( f(n) \) is multiplicative and given by the product of \( (1 - p_i) \) for each distinct prime \( p_i \). To find \( f(2023) \), we factorize 2023 into its prime factors: \( 2023 = 7 \times 17^2 \). Using the multiplicative property of \( f \), we calculate: \[ f(2023) = f(7) \cdot f(17^2) \] Since \( f(p) = 1 - p \) for a prime \( p \) and \( f(p^k) = 1 - p \) for any prime power \( p^k \), we have: \[ f(7) = 1 - 7 = -6 \quad \text{and} \quad f(17^2) = 1 - 17 = -16 \] Thus, \[ f(2023) = (-6) \cdot (-16) = 96 \] The final answer is \(\boxed{96}\).
